Date: 16 Nov 2000
From: Laurence J. Gleeson <oiercu@loxinfo.co.th>

Susceptibility of African Elephant to Foot and Mouth Dis.: RFI
--------------------------------------------
A recent ProMED-mail posting included information from a Reuters report
(V2000 #270) about the likelihood of Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD)
infections in wildlife in the current FMD outbreak in South Africa. In the
last sentence it states the elephants would not be affected. It is clear
the Asian elephant is quite susceptible to FMD and the disease can cause
very severe lameness. I wonder could someone clarify the matter of
susceptibility of the African elephant for the sake of accuracy in the
ProMED-mail record?
--
Laurence J. Gleeson
OIE SEAFMD Regional Co-ordination Unit
c/o Faculty of Veterinary Medicine
Kasetsart University
Chatuchak, Bangkok, 10900
THAILAND
<oiercu@loxinfo.co.th>
[Enlightenment was sought and the following was received from Roy Bengis, a
very experienced South African wildlife veterinarian with many years in the
Kruger National Park. - Mod.MHJ
